segments.text: Okay, reading from my actual log book here.
On the 20th of December, that's up at Kunming, I would add it to you, shot down eight out of ten Jap bombers.
And that was a one hour and 30 minute flight, by the way, including the scramble time and all.
And that's the one where the intelligence said the other two never did get across the border.
And to your credit, there were two kills?
Yes.
They paid me for two on that flight, yeah.
Now, the 26th of January, I sure as shot down three Jap I-97 fighters in a 45-minute flight.
Then it wasn't the 29th of January like we've been saying.
It was the 26th of January.
You shot down three over Rangoon.
Yeah.
Okay, we'll get that right on the tape.
25th of February shot down one Jap I-97.
Okay well let's talk about that one then.
That's your that's your next combat success.
25th of February 1942, where were you?
Oh wait a minute.
26th January 1942, shot down three Jap I-97 fighters.
Now that's the one we were talking about.
Yeah we just
I've got down three, and in my diary I said two.
Yeah.
You better fix that in your diary.
I think I said two in one probable.
Isn't that what I said?
In the diary, you said two in one probable.
In your logbook, you say three.
Yeah.
In this logbook, right.
You see, that's the reason I had to edit this.
Now we're talking about the next combat victory mission that you had, the 25th of February, 1942.
And where were you at this time?
At Rangoon.
And you'd been flying missions throughout the time from the 26th of January to the 25th of February, but this is the next kill that you had.
Yeah, yeah.
Would you describe that?
About this time, I caught sight of a Jap formation.
Neil came on the radio, come on over here, here they are.
I thought to myself, where in the hell is here?
And started in on the bombers I saw.
There were 14 in perfect V formation.
Suddenly I caught sight of that usual cluster formation of Japanese fighters directly above the bombers and changed my mind.
I had to get some altitude speed.
I ended up making my first attempt on the fighters, and this one was head on.
He caught fire before I closed in to the point where I had to pull up to miss him.
I looked for another and reached up with a pad on the charging handle of a .50 caliber gun."
I had a tendency to do that every time I would knock a fighter down.
Pat the gun.
And so you were coming straight in on this one, and he was coming straight in at you.
A lot of times this happened.
And you hit him?
Yeah.
He didn't hit you?
No.
Again, I ended up in a head-on attack.
They were equally as aggressive as we were.
We headed straight at each other, each with all our guns blazing.
At what...
It seemed to be the last second he pulled up, and I had decided to do the same thing at the same time.
This is the one I was telling you about a while ago.
Oh, okay.
It is more natural, G-force-wise, to pull up than to push over.
I reacted, it seemed, unconsciously, as I shoved forward on a stick violently.
As tight as my seatbelt was, and boy, did we put him tight in expectation of combat.
My head hit the top of my canopy.
We shot past each other, him above me.
I rolled and pulled violently to the left, straining my head over backwards to pick him up.
He, too, was inflamed.
Yow!
Two in less than three minutes.
Now, this is, see how I'm getting them mixed up?
This is the next day.
Yeah.
Now, this is the 25th of February I'm reading from.
Well, your logbook says the 26th of February.
The 25th of February.
That's for one.
Oh, yeah.
The 26th.
Two, yeah.
Two.
You've got some work to do on that.
Well, this is the first time I've put it together.
I typed this for the first time out of my original diary.
Well, that describes some of the combat anyhow, whether my days are right or not.
So the 25th of February, you shot down one.
The 26th of February, you shot down two more.
Yeah.
Which brings us up to a total of eight.
Right, and there it is, Detroit 8 airplane.
On March 1942, before the strafing attack on Chiang Mai.
Now this is after we had evacuated from Rangoon.
So you left, when did you leave Rangoon?
Right after the 26th of February?
Did I say 27th?
27th.
At 27th.
You left Rangoon.
On the 27th, and landed and operated out of Magwe, M-A-G-W-E, Burma, on the 28th of February.
Okay, so you went up to Burma, and how are the conditions there?
This is where you begin to see the usual pandemonium and mix-up of
war front, particularly when you're losing and retreating.
The Japanese were pushing up from Singapore, up the peninsula, come across into Rangoon, Burma, and taking over that base, and they were pushing up north towards China.
And see, we were evacuating north up to Irrawaddy River.
That's Mogwe right there.
Here is Rangoon, Mogwe.
No, wait a minute.
No, it's up here.
Right up here.
OK.
This is Mogli right here.
That's Tangu.
OK.
But it's right in this area.
Yeah.
OK. How did you get them?
Could you describe the conditions of Mogli?
The remnants of the RAF air base.
and strictly RAF, the remnants of what had escaped from Singapore.
And they had a shambles of a light bomber Blenheim outfit remaining, five or six airplanes.
They had a couple of old Lysander
observation airplanes, which were practically useless for observation and photo reconnaissance, if you will.
And they had about four or five hurricanes.
And they were hoping for reinforcements immediately from India, you know, to come across.
And, of course, they were delighted for us to stay with them because we were, you know, still fighting for them.
You began to see refugees, you know, and that's the thing that you remember so well.
that shows the effects of war on a countryside.
Peasants with what belongings they have left and carts drawn by oxen or Indian water buffalo.
Some wealthy people apparently and a nice little foreign car, Japanese automobile.
And the city just overflown.
We had, the only place we had at Montgomery was tents.
The British put up some tents for us, because they didn't have anything else.
And if I remember correctly, we had, I think we had about six airplanes.
We had to leave one airplane at random, we couldn't get out.
And because we had robbed it before to get the others out.
I think we had about six airplanes.
Of course, six pilots were flying, including me and Bob Neal.
Incidentally, two of the boys got lost on the way up because of sandstorms.
Again, no navigation aid.
But fortunately, they found open field where they could land, and we got those airplanes back.
So you only left with six, and you went down there with, what, 12?
Well, you know, we had airplanes going back and replaced with parts.
We lost training-wise.
several airplanes in Rangoon.
But actual combat, in actual combat, if I can remember correctly, I think we lost, in actual combat, eight pilots.
At Rangoon or the whole time?
No, throughout the entire AVG history.
Wow.
And now, we lost more airplanes than that because, see, the pilots bailed out.
I bailed out of an airplane once, see, and I'm still there.
So we lost more airplanes than that.
We eventually got our 100 airplane, just about the time I left 42, and I helped ferry some of them, the P-40E.
But let's get back to the conditions now.
The people were crowding into the cities, and how about you slept in tents, and that was it.
How about the bugs?
I never remember any bad bugs until China.
About a quarter of them were in China.
We really got in a mess of those.
Mosquitoes?
I don't remember mosquitoes bothering us.
I remember at Mogwe, the tents weren't too bad.
It was cool.
Hot in the day, so you want to be cool at night.
I don't ever remember mosquitoes bothering us anyplace.
Were you on the floor or on the couch?
No, we were in the couch.
And we had mosquito nets, too.
In fact, one of the main things in Burma was mosquito nets.
Never anything bothered me except some ants got on me one time.
I think it was because I had some sweets nutting hair oil on my hair.
I woke up with them all over my head.
Bed bugs, definitely in Ling Ling, China.
A gift store came home in August.
I was practically eaten alive with those.
Plus bed, I was fed some tongue oil, you know, tongue nut.
You make paint oil out of it, mixed with paint.
I'm getting ahead of myself, but the Chinese went down and bought that instead of cooking oil to cook their fish in.
And the whole outfit got sick, including Johnny Allison, who we're just going to continue doing.
At Ma Gui, we ate at the British Mess, and this was getting pretty sparse then.
I remember having beer and toast for breakfast several times.
That's all.
Beer and toast?
Hot beer and toast.
Why hot beer?
Well, that was all I had.
Didn't have any ice.
I don't remember any decent coffee at all in Burma.
In China, we got some better coffee, but I didn't get good coffee until I came back to India.
Who was supplying you?
RAF at that time.
The RAF was supplying you.
Was Chenault with you?
No, Chenault was still up in China.
We were communicating with him through British communications, RAF.
They kept a link with him, actually.
And radio teletype.
How many squadrons did he have?
He still had three.
We always had three.
I know you always had three, but how many were with him in China?
Two.
Two, and you were down there on your own.
He had the what?
We weren't engaged in any fighting in China at the time because of the Burma campaign.
And he was using the reserve forces up at Kunming to rotate and see the squadron.
We were the last squadron to go down to Kunming.
And I think it, I mean, Rangoon.
And I think even while we were there, he even rotated a few aircraft, took some of our bummers and sent some better ones.

maintained one to us without rotating another squadron down he kept us there towards the end it mocked we finally he pulled all of us out and replaced us with about six more college and matter of fact he brought a whole squadron down at that time this will be interesting to you uh general the old ground pounder
And General Fennel got in a horrible argument that went clear to the top between President Roosevelt and General Esselstyn about ground support for General Stillwell's troops.
I had met General Stillwell once or twice.
I actually sat under a wing of an airplane and talked with him.
He was quite a dedicated old man.
ground pounder type, if you will.
Real dedicated old gentleman.
He looked more like a, you pardon it, a college professor in English rather than a military.
I'm glad I wasn't interested.
No, I mean, he looked to be, John Stilwell, he looked to be then about 65.
No kidding, yeah.
He was lean and wore some old steel rim spectacles and had a burr cut haircut.

skinny old skinny as a rail and wore typical ground pounder old uniform rag taggle type but more dedicated to his task and he was be damned that Burma if the Japs were going to run him out of Burma he would be damned if they did and he was trying to get all of our measly three squadrons if you will Chinese Air Force dedicated to nothing more of a ground support of him
if his troops in the jungle.
And of course, we weren't about to do that.
Why not?

Well, General Chenault knew better, and when it began to trickle down to the pilots that General Chenault might be losing this battle and we'd have to do it, this is one time that morale of the flying target began to get pretty low.
You couldn't, you just can't visualize until you see it.
Trying to support
Well, it's sort of like the Vietnamese War, trying to support some, if you will, jungle fighters in the jungles that are so thick with trees that range anywhere from 100 feet to 200 feet high.
No way to see them.
Plus the fact that operate that low with a P-40 and no way to dive away should the Zeros come in and get on top of you, you're a dead duck.
And we knew it.
And boy, we just... One squadron was ready to...
Throwing a towel had the Generalissimo, I had General Chennault do it.
Had Stillwell.
Had his way.
So Chennault and Stillwell were arguing about this.
Oh, violent enemies.
They were worse than General Chennault and General Hepburn.
But through the Gissimo, Generalissimo, General Chennault won his argument and said, no, first priority is still the air defense.
And so none of us had to do.
There were two or three missions flown on this, and boy, the pilots, they didn't like it at all.
I never went on a mission like that, but I wouldn't have liked it either.
How could you help them?
I mean, how could you give them any support if you couldn't find them?
That's it.
It was worthless.
It was absolutely worthless.
Useless.
And it was almost a suicide flight should a Japanese come over the interception.
And what did you think of Stilwell?
Well, that's the reason I didn't like him.
Because he was being unreasonable.
He was one of the older types, and I really don't think he understood air power.
Plus the fact that at that time, just at the starting of the war, air power hadn't really made itself known.
And I don't think he understood it at all.
We would have done it had we been ordered to do it, but General Chenault, I'm sure, would have been the last man to agree with it.
Now, when you were, you said before that you were sitting underneath an airplane with Stilwell.
Tell me about that.
I just had, he was waiting for a pilot in nearby Gutenberg to take him.
It was one of these things, he'd been down to talk to Schmeltz, he'd been back at Chung King, and during his time he was talking about this fight that was going on.
At that particular time I was sitting with him, I didn't know all this background.
This was the early days of it.
Like I told you, I gave my impression of him as an elderly old boy.
He talked to me.
Never asked me many questions about my combat experience or how you're doing or anything.
I guess he was preoccupied with thought.
I didn't, at that time, I'm not sure I realized really how big a man he was.
But later on, later on, you know, knowing what I, learning what I did, that's the reason I have no respect for him.
As a military, as an army commander, I'm sure that the old boy was dedicated, and he had his objective and had his job, but he was completely, to do what he wanted to do was completely unreasonable.
No way.
And it was not enough.
Finally what happened was the Chinese stopped the Japanese at the northern reaches of Burma
the Mekong River.
The Chinese actually stopped them.
They never did actually penetrate the southern border of China.
Then the Japanese decided to come
from the north down too.
So Stilwell never did reject or eject the Japanese out of northern Burma.
Eventually, they just withdrew because of higher priorities in other areas when they began to lose the war.
But at any rate, Stilwell lost his battle with the old man, and we continue to do everything.
OK. Now, how long were you at?
Now, I and my bunch, the first squadron, we were replaced by one of the other squadrons, partially, and there were only six airplanes.
We went on back up to Kunming.
This was in early February, I believe.
No, early March.

The short after we left Magui, by the way, the base was real hard hit by the Japanese, and we lost, one pilot was killed on the ground, one of our pilots was killed on the ground from bombing, and we lost about two or three aircraft.
And the British evacuated down, of course, so did we.
Then we backed up clear into lower wing across, right across the river into southern China.
And in effect,
turn Burma over to the Japanese.
Then we operated out of lower wing on the same type of mission.
Were you disappointed about losing Burma?
Looking back now, yeah, we were disappointed.
It looked as though the Japanese were winning the war.
We were being squeezed back up into China.
As a matter of fact, at times we'd sit in bull sessions
and figure at the end of our year's contract, say September, how in the world would we get out of China?
The Japanese had the coast block, now they had the south block of Burma, and we dreamed up ways to go through the Himalayas some way back down through Afghanistan into India.
course never turned out to be that way.
Then of course they developed the, that's one reason they developed the hump route with air and even tried to build a Lido road across it to get supplies into China.
And that's what generated the Chiang Mai raid.
Chiang Mai, Thailand.
Okay, that was, okay, that was your next major raid.
For our squadron.
I mean for you.
Oh, for me, right.
I'm not talking aboutI'm talking about you.
See, we drew the two squadrons back up into Kunming, and then eventually had to operate with one of them in Lower Wing, one in Lower Wing and two in Kunming.
And then, you know, to get back into war, the old man dreamed up this mission.
And when was this?
Well, now that'smaybe it's helpful in this time.
Yeah, I'm reflecting.
Yes, Strait of Jaffa Aerodrome at Chiang Mai, 25th of March.
25th of March.
And where is that?
Can you come in?
Yeah, yeah.
You know, strange as it is, I mean, it's coincidentally, subsequently we get to it.
See, I was in the Southeast Asian War, like you were, and I was assigned Thailand.
I was Deputy Commander of 1312th Air Force.
It, uh...
Udorn, and I visited the detachment up at Chiang Mai, Thailand, the very air base that I hit, if I'm not kidding.
That must have been fascinating.
So it's north of Bangkok.
Chiang Mai is the
Summer capital, here we are, Chiang Mai.
It's Chiang Mai.
So it's close to the Burma border.
Yeah, it's right across the Burma border.
It's the Saline River.
Northwest Thailand.
Northwest Thailand, yeah.
C-H-A-N-G-M-A-I.
C-H-I-A-N-G. Oh, okay.
Capital M-A-I.
Chiang Mai, Thailand.
We'll get that right.
And that was on 25th of March.
Tell me about that raid.
Why did he want to dream this up?
Wasn't air defense enough?
Wasn't that enough of a chore?
We couldn't get to the Japanese Air Force.
They wouldn't come to Kunming anymore.
They knew they'd lose everything they had.
Lower Wing, they were taking Burma, so why come up at Lower Wing and suffer air defense missions and lose airplanes like they've been losing at Rangoon?
So...
We weren't engaging them.
The old man began to get impatient, so we began to figure out how to...
So for a month, you didn't have any contact with them?
Well, at Lower Wing, yeah, they'd have, every once in a while, they'd mix up down there, and they knocked a few airplanes down in northern Burma, trying to attack them.
But we up at Kunming didn't do a thing.
We had to get a scare sometime and scramble.
Well, we don't scramble, sure, but never did meet them.
Well, the old man thought this mission at Chiang Mai, Thailand, he threw the intelligence, was the headquarters of the entire Southeastern Japanese Air Force, all Southeast Asia.
And he knew that they were planning a hell of a big push to support the army in penetrating southern China.
And they were massing their aircraft, primarily at Chiang Mai, Thailand.
They get this through intelligence sources.
So he called Bob Neal in and Jack Newkirk.
I don't know if you ever heard of Jack Newkirk, but he was the commander of the second squadron at that time.
Bob Neal was the commander of the first squadron.
And sat down and discussed this plan he had that we were to take off with 14 airplanes.
Jack Newkirk would have four and, well, we were going to take
14 airplanes.
He hadn't decided who would take them yet.
And he was going to hit Chiang Mai, Thailand with a surprise dawn attack.
Now mind you, some of these pilots that were flying these airplanes, P-40s, had never taken one off at night.
We had one pilot in our squadron that was from the Navy
And if I remember correctly, I don't think he ever flew a combat airplane at night, just a training airplane.
But anyway.
But did you have any fire planes?
Wouldn't you need some bombers for this mission?
Sure, but this was straight.
We didn't have any bombers.
This is the old man.
The only way you could do it, we had to trace them.
Did the P-40 take any bombs?
Later on, we actually had desperation.
We, as a matter of fact, killed two of our best pilots already.
That's another story.
Bob Little.
Tremendous.
Ace.
Okay, so... See, that's all us supporting Stillwell again.
You had no bombs on this mission?
No.
It's strictly strafing.
Okay.
And the way we planned this flight, we were to go over to Lower Wing, refuel, and looking at the map,
you find low wing is just across the border from northern Burma, much closer to Chiang Mai.
So you're going to refuel there the day before, sleep overnight, get up in the morning, and go at dawn.
Refuel and get everything ready.
Then late that evening, just before dusk, we would take off and fly to another little RAF base in northern, northeastern Burma,
back up in a pocket to the eastern part of Burma and the north where the Japanese hadn't got to.
There's no reason for them to even be in the area because there's no valuable economic...
The railroad went due north through Lascio and Mo Wing along the Burma Road.
But there's a little RAF base that's still held there in support for maybe reconnaissance or observation planes.
It was right across the border from Thailand, very close to Chiang Mai.
Well, we were going to slip in there just before...
night so that, you know, Japanese, nobody would suspect us.
Or if somebody did, they'd have less time to alert the Japanese for the planned dawn attack.
Now, that's what we did, and it ended up where Bob Neal was picked by the old man, General Chenault, to command the mission, much to old Jack Newkirk's
He was a very spirited type, fine guy, ex-Navy pilot.
He had the second squadron.
And I'm saying this for a particular reason.
He was killed in the mission, but he became very downcast.
He went along with it after the old man made the decision, but he would be the second in command.
And furthermore, he would only take four airplanes out of his squadron.
Bob Neal would take ten.
I'm sorry, it would take six.
There's going to be a total of ten aircraft.
Bob Neal would take four for the attack and two for high cover.
So a total of ten airplanes.
And we had it all laid out where we'd go into this little, leave Namsang was the name of it.
Let me get the name.
Save your time, take it off me.
It was a little forward RAF base in Namsang.
We'd sleep in there at night.
How do you spell that?
N-A-M-S-A-N-G.
If it's small, you can't find it.
Really, all it is is a RAF little support base.
So you'd sleep in there.
Grass strip, about 2,000 feet long, with an operations building and one barracks.
Did you do it?
We are all recovered in there that night, 10 aircraft, 10 pilots, and no maintenance people.
The RAF agreed to have some refueling crews there to help refuel the airplane the following day after recovery.
So when the pilots got there, we parked our own airplanes, tied them down, and did everything necessary.
The pilots did this.
And by the time we got in there, it's just as dark.
Then we went over to the, all ten of us, went over to the RAF barracks and the RAF gave us dinner and we turned in early.
And I remember old Jack Newkirk, he, oh he was down, he wouldn't even matter of fact, he would hardly speak to anybody during
dinner, but all of us were excited, you know, talking about it, and he was very down-to-date.
The next, uh... Because he was second in command?
Yeah, he was second, and then, uh... And he wanted to be first?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, I nearly killed him.
He returned, uh, that's ironic when I say I nearly killed him.
He was killed in the mission.
Uh, he went to bed early.
Well, uh, we went to bed, and the next morning, we got up real, way before daylight, and we ate, we got out, ready to take off.
And we got there.
OK.
So they woke you at 4 o'clock in the morning?
Yeah.
And it was 525 before we were in a cockpit warming up the planes.
I'm going to have to correct this reading from my diary.
There were eight of us.
The two top cover guys were back at lower wing, and they were to come over and join us, rendezvous with us.
Okay.
So there were eight of you.
Yeah.
Some had never taken a plane off at night.
Remember, this was before daylight.
Even I had not taken the P-40 off at night.
Yet these thoughts apparently never entered the minds of these guys.
Checking my diary notes, I think back on these moments.
It was pitch dark deep in the jungle of Burma on a desolate RAF air strip with no lights whatsoever for reference.
We parked a truck at the far end of the grass strip and turned the headlights on.
This was strictly an aiming point for the takeoff.
Bob Neal earlier took off and I pointed at him.
It was 6.10 a.m. when I pushed the throttle full open
A blue exhaust flame swept around the lower side of my windshield and trailed along the two slides to the rear of my vision.
I aimed at the truck lights and felt my way along the grass strip until the wheels felt light.
Weaved at a back pressure on a stick and I was free of the ground.
I couldn't see a damn thing.
I went on instruments.
Now this is, you know, some of these young fellows hadn't even flown at night.
Flying instruments, too, in a fighter airplane.
It's rough.
My basic reference was my rate of climb indicator.
As long as it showed up, I felt reasonably assured.
A few seconds later, I relaxed to look up and see Bob's navigation lights on his plane.
There he was, slightly to the left and high.
Were you afraid?
No.
Taken off?
Tense.
Oh, no.
Just tense.
Knew he'd do it.
I followed and thought to myself, how in the hell will those other guys make it over?
How did they?
They did.
They got over.
So all eight of you were following each other's wing lights.
Well, after you get in the air, see, it's no flat airplane.
Then as you get further up in the air, you know, just as breaking dawn, daylight, you know, it gets lighter.
We were at a rendezvous over the field at 10,000 feet.
I'm glad I'm reading this out of the diary because this is correct.
A plan called for me to fly Bob's right wing in number two position, for I had flown over the area before and recognized Chiang Mai Air Base.

To go back here a minute, on Pearl Harbor Day, we were at Tangu, the whole ABG was, and we were shocked that the old man immediately ordered a flight of two of us to fly across to Chiang Mai Air Base, which was where the Japanese had taken over.
that area to see if there was any airplanes on it.
So I, and of course Bob Neal and I went, and we checked the base, and I knew the area.
There's a big mountain right by the air base, by the way.
So I knew exactly where the air base was, and that's the reason I was selected to fly next to Bob Neal's wing.
Bob had never seen a plane before.
Pappy Boyington
and Bartling were number three and four, and then came Eddie Rector and Black Mac McGarry as a top cover element of the two ships.
So that gave us six.
Jack Newkirk was leading another flight with Ed Gesselbrecht on his wing, followed by a second element of Laura and Buzz Keaton.
Well, we rendezvoused.
It'd be too much to read all this.
We rendezvoused at 10,000 feet, and...
By that time, it was a great enough day where, at that altitude, it was light enough to see each other.
We didn't need lights.
I turned off the flashlight I had between my legs and put it down in the glove compartment on the side.
Then we started off on strictly time and distance and compass course for the air base, Chiang Mai, Thailand.
And I think it was going to be about a,
30-minute flight, something like that.
It wasn't very far.
And Bob Neal was leading.
Now, Bob and I had agreed the night before.
See, I was flying on his wing.
He and I agreed that if he overshot or didn't detect this mountain and wasn't sure of where he was, I would fly up, and I did, and I felt he was going off course and was going to miss it.
I would fly up next to him, wiggle the wings, and do like this, and I would take over.
No radio transmissions.
No, this is total radio silence.
Oh, yeah.

And sure enough, as we got up towards the mountain, and I knew exactly where we were, and we got to the side of the mountain just off our left wing, when Bob should have started turning, he just kept going on.
And I knew then that he wasn't sure.
So I moved up, put my wing on my head, and he, okay.
So then he dropped back and took on my wings.
So you took command then of the attack?
I took command.
The four of us would make the attack and the other two were to give us high cover in case some Japanese airplanes got off.
See, then they would give us cover because we were going to be low.
We were going to be straking.
I thought you said there was eight of you.
Well, I'll tell you about the other two.
Two to rendezvous.
Yeah.
Okay, so you four were ready to go down?
Newkirk Flight was supposed to rendezvous with us.
He never rendezvoused with us.
We didn't know what happened until we came back.
I'll tell you that story.
So the six of us went on down.
And to get back, I started down in my turn from 10,000 feet and drove the jungle to Burma, Thailand, Southeast Asia.
It's steamy and a lot of mist and smoke in the morning, just the daylight.
